{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930071601/0675.xml":{"full_text":"Conservative Position Should Be Maintained in Market, Spectator Warni\nACTION POIIIS ID HIGHER\nPRICES FOB STOCKS\nprofessional Traders Thought to Have Tested\nMart Strength and Turned Bullish When\nPower Was Manifested\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nThe market\u2019s own action points to higher prices for the\ngood stocks. The reaction predicted came yesterday after\nnoon, but its brevity and the sudden rebound before the\nclose was a surprise. The conclusion is that at present\nspecialists\u2019 books are well supplied with buying orders on the\nway down and comparatively thin on the selling side.\nIf looks very much as though professionals sold stocks to\ntest the market\u2019s strength and. discovering the preponder\nance of buying power, turned quickly and jacked prices up\nagain. The trend for the past week is inescapable evidence\nthat the bull forces are in the saddle for the time being\nwith the acquiescence, if not active support, of the powers\nth At be. i 1\nTalk of Washington being in cahoots with leading market\noperators to start another bull movement is far-fetched, to\nsay the least. But it is very likely true that the Administra\ntion is not averse to seeing higher stock prices for the cheer\nfullness this will, and already has, engendered. Revival of the\noptimism that went glimmering with the May-June market\ndebacle would undoubtedly help things. It would encourage\nbusiness and aid thousands of small banks throughout the\ncountry, who are reported to be in danger of becoming\nembarrassed by the depreciation of their securities collateral\nagainst loans. Yet caution must still be the watchword for\nthose planning to make market commitments, and a con\nservative position should be maintained until definite evi\ndence of the long-hoped-for business revival appears.\nGood News\nThe rise in United States Steel\noperations to 63 per cent of\ncapacity this week from 56 per\ncent over the Independence Day\nholiday was good news even\nthough an upturn was expected\nIn view of the drastic holiday\nshut downs in the entire indus\ntry. Yet its market-wise influence\nwas probably very little. Steel\u2019s\nadvance in the market is at\ntributed to the highest grade of\nbuying and the Morgan-First Na\ntional interests are prominently\nmentioned. I hear the corpora\ntion itself bought stock from 159\ndown for resale to employes and\nalso that large lines of Steel\nliquidated at higher prices are\nbeing replaced.\nMeehan himself. I am told,\nbought Standard of New Jersey\non the floor of the exchange yes\nterday, and is also said to be\nbulling Radio-Keith-Orpheum. The\noils were a strong group and\ngood buying is reported in the\npetroleum leaders. The Skelly\nOil pool, is reported ready to be\ngin activity.\nA Favorite\nAmerican Telephone put up a\nsplendid exhibition yesterday,\nrising more than eight points.\nI am told this stock is probably\nthe least manipulated of the\nactive leaders and that buying\ncame from many sources and\nfrom powerful interests bullish\non the long-term prospects. Rights\non the new stock will expire\nAugust 1, which will lift the\npressure on Telephone that has\nbeen noticeable recently. The\ncompany\u2019s ability to expend its\nearnings along with the increase\nIn its capitalization is another\nstrong factor in its advance.\nStrength in National Power and\nLight is reviving the old merger\nrumors. The hook-up is expected\nto take the form\u2018of a giant hold\ning company to include American\nGas and Electric, American Power\nand Light ahd Electric Power and\nLight, all Electric Bond and\nShare affiliates. This system\nwould have huge natural gas re\nsources as well.\nThe Motors\nInsiders are reported to have\nbeen picking up the leading au\ntomobile stocks on the qui vive\nrecently. The motor stocks are\napparently thoroughly liquidated\nand the. better companies are in\nstrong cash positions. New models\nare expected to be a strong stim\nulant to sales, and the curb on\nproduction this year and low in\nventories of new cars makes the\noutlook for next year favorable\nOn the other hand, cost of re\nvamping plants to bring out the\nnew cars and the uncertainty of\nsustained public demand clouds\nthe near term outlook. However,\nstocks like General Motors, Hud\nson. Nash, Studebaker, and Au\nburn seem to be in a buying\nrange for long pull commitments\nThe better automobile accessory\nWe are pleased to announce\nthat\nMr. John Roche Howland\nhas become associated with us as manager of\nour Washington office\nG. L. Ohrstrom Co.\nINCORPORATED\nNew York SHOREHAM BLDG. Chicago\nPhiladelphia Loa A\u00bb\u201el.a\nPhone District 3241\nWASHINGTON NEWS\nstocks, as Timken and Electric\nAuto Lite, also have speculative\nappeal.\nThe Street is crediting Durant\nwith bringing about the improve\nment in the market. It was he, it\nis said, who discovered stocks\nwere oversold late in June and\nby his operations turned the whole\nlist upward. I am told that Dan\nforth, the \u201cbig Boston bear,\u201d is\nvacationing down Cape Cod way\nand has told his friends that he\n\u201cwas going to play a while and\nstay clear of the market.\u201d\nMerchandising Stocks\n_ The Street is beginning to look\nwith more favor on Montgomery\nWard and Sears Roebuck as well\nas the better department store\nstocks. These companies are\nhelped by lower commodity prices\nto reduce merchandise prices and\nthus stimulate sales. Profit mar\ngins are unlikely to be affected\nas costs are lower. Further retail\nprice reductions seem in the cards\nbefore stabilization is attained. I\nam told that sales of Montgomery\nWard and Sears Roebuck for the\nfirst two weeks of this month\nwere as good as in this period\nlast year. However, lower prices\nfor wheat and other agricultural\nproducts is an unfavorable factor.\nInterests who were bullish on\nCase Threshing several years ago\nare said to be recommending\nGleaner Combine on the curb as\na good long-pull speculation. The\nStreet is talking of 300 for Allied\nChemical before long if the\nmarket keeps going up, and I\nhear of 200 for Steel before the\nsummer is out\u2014provided the ex\npected upturn in business ma\nterializes. United Aircraft will\nmake a much better showing the\nrest of the year than it did in the\nfirst quarter, when it earned 39\ncents a share, according to Presi\ndent F. B. Rentschler.\n\u25a0\u2014T\nJohn Howland Heads\nOhrstrom Co, Here\nAnnouncement is made of the\nappointment of John Roche How\nland as manager of the Washing\nton branch of G. L. Ohrstrom\nCo., with offices in the Shore\nham Building. He comes from\nthe Philadelphia offices of the\ncompany, and was associated\nwith the Illinois Merchants Trust\nCompany, of Chicago, before af\nfiliation with the Ohrstrom or\nganization.\nG. L. Ohrstrom Co. are na\ntional distributors of conservative\ninvestment stocks and bonds and\ndevelop estates and investments.\nPublic Utilities Net\nIncreases Over 1929\nNet earnings for the month of\nMay of 95 public utility com\npanies. excluding telephone and\ntelegraph companies, totaled $86,-\n000,000, compared with $89,000.-\n000 in April and $82,000,000 in\nMay. 1929. the Department of\nCommerce reported today.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nOfficial\nit fl\nI\nI\nnk I\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nJOHN B. LARNER\nWELL-KNOWN Washington\nbanker and financial expert\nwho was named to a vice\npresidency in the official list\nof the National Union Life In\nsurance Company at a meet\ning yesterday.\nWTM\nMEND\nMissouri Kansas Texas Rail\nroad Company C\u2019Katy\u201d) direc\ntors today declared another divi\ndend of $1 a share on the com\nmon stock, payable September 30\nto holders of record September 5.\nOn June 3 an initial dividend of\n$1 was paid.\nOppenheim Collins\nOppenheim Collins Company\ndirectors today reduced the pay\nment on the common stock by\ndeclaring a quarterly dividend of\n75 cents a share, placing the\nstock on $3 annual rate against\nthe $4.50 previously paid. Isaac\nD. Levy, president, stated that\nthe reduction was being made in\naccordance with the policy of the\ncompany to add regularly to the\nundivided profits of the com\npany.\nMohawk Mining\nMohawk Mining Company di\nrectors today halved the payment\non the common stock by de\nclaring a dividend of 75 cents a\nshare against the $1.50 paid\nthree months ago.\nUnited Engineering\nUnited Engineering and Foun\ndry Company directors today de\nclared the usual extra dividend\nof 35 cents a share and the regu\nlar quarterly dividend of 40\ncents a share payable August 8\nto holders of record July 29.\nFederal Electric\nThe Federal Electric Company,\nInc., declared an initial quarterly\ndividend of $1.75 a share on its\n$7 no-par preferred stock and a\nquarterly dividend of $1.50 on its\n$6 no-par preferred.\nRoyal Dutch\nThe. Chase National Bank, as\nsuccessor depositary of certain\nordinary stock of the Royal Dutch\nCompany, under an agreement\ndated September 10, 1918, an\nnounced that it had received a\ndividend of 14 guilders for each\n100 guilders par value of such\nstock held by it. This is the final\ndividend for 1929. The equiva\nlent distributable to holders of\n\u201cNew York shares\u201d under the\nagreement is $1,875 a share.\nNew Automobile\nStocks Decrease\nLow production level in the\nautomobile industry not only is\nclearing dealers\u2019 shelves of new\ncars to a point where shortages\nare likely to develop with any\nstimulation in buying, but is en\nabling dealers to concentrate on\nthe liquidation of used car stocks.\nIt was estimated that total\nstocks on June 1 were equal to\napproximately one month\u2019s sup\nply with calculations indicating\na stock of around 417,000 unsold\ncars at that time. At present,\ntotal stocks probably are con\nsiderably under 400,000 units.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nMEMBERS\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nI\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nChain Store Prices\nDeclared Lower in\nProfessor\u2019s Review\nWidespread discussion as to\nwhether chain stores actually\nundersell individually owned\nstores has led Prof. Malcolm D.\nTaylor, of the University of North\nCarolina, to conduct a survey in\nan effort to arrive at the truth.\nThe results of his study, pub\nlished in the July number of the\nHarvard Business Review, shows\nthat the prices of 60 well-known\ngrocery items were more than 13\nper cent cheaper in chain stores\nthan in independent stores, 13.79\nper cent to be precise.\nProf. Taylor selected Durham\nas a typical North Carolina city,\nthe fourth in size in the State,\nwith an estimated population of\n48,600. Ten seniors of the uni\nversity\u2019s school of commerce made\nthe investigation. The work was\nvoluntary. The students co-oper\nated because they were interested\nin the subject. They were in\nstructed carefully and every pre\ncaution was taken to insure ac\ncuracy.\nSeventy-three nationally-adver\ntised articles were selected for\ncomparison prices. This number\nwas finally reduced to 60 in order\nto avoid confusion over items\npacked in more than one size or\nweight. Every grocery store in\nthe city was visited by the inves\ntigators.\nDiscussing the 13.79 per cent\naverage saving in the chain\nstores, the report said:\n\u201cObjection may be made to\nthe brands selected for study\non the ground that soaps are\ngiven too much weight. Omit\nting the five soap products\nWeek's Oil Output\nDrops to 68,853 Bbls.\nDaily average production of\ncrude oil in the United States for\nthe week ended July 12 totaled\n2.541,430 barrels, a decrease cf\n68,853 barrels, according to the\nOil and Gas Journal.\nFLORSHEIIT DECLARES\nThe board of directors of the\nFlorsheim Shoe Company de\nclared a quarterly dividend of 75\ncents per share on the class A\ncommon stock of the company.\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furnished by W. b Hibba Co.)\nSALES\nWashington Gas 6s B, sloo\u00a9\n105.\nNorfolk and Washington Steam\nbots rts. w.i., 9\u00a9 16.\nFederal-American and Commer\ncial. 10@30. 5\u00a930, 5@30.\nNational Mortgage and Invest\nment preferred, 65@4%.\nAFTER CALL\nPotomac Electric s*/2 per cent\npreferred, 20 107 */2.\nMergenthaler Linotype, 12\u00a9\n96%.\nWashington Railway and Elec\ntric 4s, sl,ooo@B6 1 4 $1,000@86%,\nssoo\u00a9 86.\nPublic Utility Bond. I Bid |A\u00abk\u2019.l\nAmer Tel Telga llis \u201933..1101\nAmer Tel Telga 4 >4\" \u201939.1163 I\nAm T T C\u2019fl Tr 6s .11115441\nAnacoslia Pot R R 55...1 S 3 I\nAna A Pot Guar 5s 1 94\nC P Tel of Va 5s 1102 I\nCapital Traction R R 55...1 92 I 94\nCity Suburban 55... I 80 I S 3\nGeorgetown Gas Ist 5s 1101*41104\nPotomac Elec Cons 5s 1102*41103 44\nPotomac Elec 6s 1107 I\nWash Alex Mt V Ctf....l I\nWash Bal to An ss. .......1 65 I\nWashington Gas 5s 1103 1105\nWash Gas 6 series A 1102 1103\nWash Gas 6s series B 1105 1106*,4\nWash Ry A Elec I 86 I *1\nMiscellaneous Bonds I I\nBarber.: Ross Inc .6*4 b I 89 I 90\nChevy Chase Club 5 44s HOO 1.....\nD C Paper Mfg 6s I 50 I 75\nW. M. Cold Storage 5s .1 95 I\nwash Cons Title 6s 89141100\nPublie Utility Stocks I I\ndAmer Tel A *Te1..........|21\u00ab%|.....\nCapitol Traction Co \u2019..1 59441 62\n\u2666Wash Gas Lt Co 1115 132\nd- N W Steamboat 215 255\nN W Steamboat rts W I 16 16%\nPot Elec Power 6s ptd.... 11014 112\nPot Elec Pwr s*4s ptd 107 44 108\nWash' Ry El com 550\nWash Ry El ptd 98 99\nWash Balt An com 5\nWash Balt A: An ptd I 5\nNational' Bank Stocks I I\nCapital 1230 1250\nColumbia ....1400 1450\nCommercial .....1250 1235\nDistrict 1213 1250\nFederal-American 1275 1300\nLiberty ..1200 1230\nLincoln 1400 *436\nMetropolitan 1335 '365\nThe National Daily\nfrom the lilt the average\nsaving at chain stores is 13.03\nper cent. Omitting eight com\nmodities on which the largest\nsaving is shown the average\nsaving on 52 articles becomes\n12.07 per cent.\n\u201cIt is a safe assumption,\nhowever, that Vie additional\ncharges incident to the offer\ning of delivery service, charge\naccounts, and the taking of\ntelephone orders by indepen\ndent stores do not amount to\n13 per cent of sales, or any\nfigure approaching that. The\nonly conclusion, then, that one\ncan draw is that, at least in\nDurham, N. C., chain stores do\noffer an appreciable saving to\nconsumers.\n\u201cProgressive independent gro\ncers can operate and are com\npeting with the chains. Many\n.consumers will continue to de\nmand the additional services\nwhich the independents render.\nSome customers cannot afford\nto pay cash while others wish\nto telephone their orders and\nhave the merchandise delivered.\nIt is questionable whether one\ncan justify the effort and\nmoney now being spent in this\nState in denouncing chain\nstores. Such practices in the\nlong run are bound to react\nagainst the independents. Or\nganisations of independent mer\nchants could profitably empha\nsise methods of improving\nretailing and group buying and\neducate retailer members in\nthe most economical and effi\ncient ways of conducting their\nbusinesses.\u201d\nBuick to Come Out\nWith New B\u2019s Line\nThe Buick Motor Company will\nproduce a full line of eight\ncylinder cars in the coming year.\nA public announcement will be\nmade on July 26.\nCrude Rubber Stocks\nIncrease at London\nLondon crude rubber stocks on\nJuly 12 totaled 80,501 tons, an\nincrease of 411 tons over preced\ning week.\ni Bld I Ask\nRiggs 147 5 |525\nSecond TSO 1220\nWashington 8240 |260\nTrust Company Stocks I I\nAmer Sec A Tr Co ..1375 1415\nContinental Trust 1120 1140\nMerch Bk A Tr 1125 ;150\n.Natl Sav A Tr 1540 1585\nUnion Trust 1245 1275\nWash Loan A Tr... 1470 510\nSavings Bank Stocks I i\nBank of Bethesda I 59 I 65\nCom. and Savings 1330 I\nEast Washington I 20 I 35\nPot Savings Bank .........I 65 I 75\nSec. Sav. Com. Bank I4W, 1500\nSeventh Street 1315\nUnited States 1530\nWash. Mechanics I 59\nFire insurance Stocks\nAmerican 1300\nCorcoran 1150 200\nFiremen\u2019s 36 44 40\nNational Union I 22 26\nTitle Insurance Stocks\nColumbia I B*il 12\nReal Estate [l5O 175\nTitle Inv Md com 20 30\nMlaeella pea Stocks I I\nBarber k(.\u00bba Inc com I 15 I 18\nChevy Ch Dairy pfd 1103 1109\nCol Sand A Grav pfd I 88%l 94\nD C. Paper Mfg pfd. I 10 I.\nDist Natl Sec pfd... 70 I 85\nEmer Bronio-Selt A 30 I 33\nFederal Storage pfd... 110 1125\nFed-Am Co Com 30 I 33\nFed-Am Co pfd 99 1101\nLanston Monotype 114441118*4\nMet Tr Stge com 104 1108\nMer Tr A Stge pfd I 95\u201941 98\nMergenthaler Lino I 96*4i 97\u20194\nNatl Mtge A Inv pfd I 4%1 514\nPeoples Drug S pfd... 1103 1106\nReal Est M G pfd I 6141 7\nSecurity Storage ...1113 1117\nTer Ref A Wh Corp I 47 I 52\nThe Carpel Corp I 22*41 24\nW Meeh Mtge Com I 9141 10\nWash Med Bldg Corp I 93 I\nWdwd A Lothrop pfd ,105 |ll2\n\u2022Exdividend.\n<lEx-Rights.\nW. LWhen issued.\nIt is not necessary\nto have had an Ac\ncount at this Bank to\nBorrow,\nEasy to Pay\nMonthly\nDeposit\nFor 12\nLoan Month*\n$l2O SIO.OO\nSIBO $15.00\n$240 $20.00\nS3OO $25.00\n$360 $30.00\n$540 $45.00\n$1,200 SIOO.OO\n$6,000 SSOO 00\nTHE MORRIS\nPLAN BANK\nUnder Snnervtslnn It. S Treasury\n1408 H STREET N. W.\nWASHINGTON n. C-\nWEDNESDAY, JULY 16, 1930\nEARLY BUDGETS\nFOB THIS YEAR\n.INGHEASED\nAdditional Millions Have Been\nAppropriated for New Plant\nImprovements and Care\nThe steel Industry\u2014barometer\nof U. S. business\u2014has no qualms\nabout the .future.\nAdditional millions have been\nappropriated in the last few days\nfor plant additions and improve\nments.\nThese new programs bring\nthe total funds appropriated for\nexpansion this .year close to half\na billion dollars. Most of this\nwork already had been contracted\nfor. Some of it has been finished,\nbut the great bulk calls for com\npletion in the last half of this\nyear with some carry over into\nnext spring.\nThe sooner other industries fol\nlow steel\u2019s lead the quicker will\ncome the business upturn.\n$20,000,000 for J. L.\nJones and Laughlin, the inde\npendent Pittsburgh steel company\ncontrolled by the founders' fam\nilies. is spending $20,000,000. Most\nof this money has been appropri\nated in the last month and will\nbe spent this year.\nRepublic Steel Corporation, the\nnew $350,000,000 company formed\nby Cyrus Stephen Eaton and his\nassociates, has completed two\nthirds of a $15,000,000 program.\nThe balance of the program will\nbe finished this summer. A\nfurther program, calling for the\nexpenditure of several additional\nmillions, is slated for announce\nment later this summer.\nYoungstown Sheet Tube Co.,\nwhiSh Mr. Eaton is seeking to\nprevent from merging with Beth\nlehem Steel Corp., has on \u201cice\u201d\na $12,000,000 expansion program.\nJames A. Campbell, Sheet\nTube\u2019s 76-year-old chairman, says\nthe work will be started as soon\nas the trial, now on jn Youngs\ntown, is completed. Eaton has\noffered to advance him the $12,-\n000,000 to carry on the work, but\nThe following newspipers are included in HEARST CONSOLIDATED PUBLICATIONS,\nNew Yoax Evening )oumrt Chicam Evening American PrrmuaoH Sun-Tele graph Dmorr Timet\nSam F*j\u00df>chco Examiner, Coll-Bulletin Oaxlanb Port-Enquirer Loa Amoxlxs Examiner, Evening Hereto\nSbattlx Port-lntelligencer Twx Amzxicam Whilt\nEarning Power\u2014the\nUltimate Test\nInvestors rightly regard earnings\u2014past, current and prospective\n\u2014as the paramount factor in determining the investment value of\ncapital stock. Market fluctuations ignored; sustained and increas\ning earnings are ultimately reflected in enhanced value of the stock.\nConsider the established earning power of\nHearst Consolidated Publications, Inc.\n7% Cumulative Participating Class A Stock\nPreferred as to assets and dividends r\nAnnual Nat Timos Dividend\nEarnings Available Requirements on\nYEAR for Dividends Class A Steck\n1926 $10,009,806 2.86\n1927 10,162,284 2.90\n1928 11,044,777 3.15.\n1929 12,854,626 3.67\nAverage $11,017,873 3.14\nBecause of this impressive record of demonstrated earning power\"\nwe recommend this stock for investment at\n$25 a Share\nApplication will be made to list iiii st -k on the New York Curb,\nChicago, San Francisco and Los Angeles Stock Exchanges.\n\nArrangements have been made with the institution* listed below to accept subscriptions\nto this issue at their ofices, or any of their branch oficesi\nThe National City Company Continental Illinois Bank and Trust Company\nAnglo London Paris Company Crocker First Company Bank of America\nSan Francisco San Francisco of California\nBank of Italy, N. T. s. A.\nSan Francisco\n1 11 4\nHEARST CONSOLIDATED PUBLICATIONS, Inc.\nSubscriptions to this stock will be THE WASHINGTON TIMES CO.\nreceived nt The Washington Times Stock Sales Department\nCompany\u2019s business office. Stock 1317-21 H St. N. W., Washington, D. C.\nSales Department, 1317 H St. Kindly send full details about your 7% shares,\nN. W., Washington, D. C, or at\nthe cashier\u2019s office of any Hearst Name\n/'si\nnewspaper or corporation in the\nUnited States, Address\n-1 t 1 \u25a0asaagsga\u00dfaag\u00dfaasggagggagac\u00dft\u00dfMMagaH\nElected j\nJU\n\u2014Hafrla-Ewlng Photo\nB. F. SAUL\nPROMINENT LOCAL realtor,\nwho was elected a vice presi\ndent of the National Union\nLife Insurance Company at a\nmeeting of the board of di\nrectors of the firm.\nCampbell has to date refused the\noffer.\nNational Steel Corp., another\nnewcomer, is putting the finish\ning touches to a $25,000,000 new\nmill at Detroit. This mill will\nbe ready for use this fall.\n$5,000,030 For Otis\nOtis Steel Co., of Cleveland,\ntoday announces work will start\nwithin 90 days on a $5,000,000 1\ncontract. A new continuous roll\ning mills is to be constructed.\nThis company is looking into\nthe alloy steel field. If it decides\nto enter this field another mill\nwill be constructed.\nBig Decline in Net\nOs Bohn Aluminum\nBohn Aluminum and Brass Cor\nporation reports for the six\nmonths ended June 30 net profit\nof $688,766, equivalent to $1.95 a\nshare on 352,418 no par common\nshares. This compares with\n$1,781,579 or $5.08 a share on 350,-\n831 shares in the same 1929 period.\nBROKERS GAIL\nSTOCKS GOOD\nFOR RISE\nOptimistic Forecast Is Made by\nLeading Wall Street Brokers\nIn Statements Issued\nBelief that the trend of the\nmarket had turned upward was\nheralded in financial circles to\nday. While some technical reac\ntions were believed inevitable no\ngreat importance was attached to\nthem. The long side of the mar\nket was considered the best at\nthis time.\nThe day-tcHlay strength is\nprobably based on the technical\nsituation plus some new bull spon\nsorship from the professionals\non the floor. New commitments\nshould be postponed unless they\nare on the scalping basis or to\nhold over on the long term.\u2014H.\nF. HUTTON CO.\nThe action of the market em\nphatically demonstrates that the\nline of least resistance is toward\nhigher levels. Chances are favor\nable for further advance before\nthe market encounters any im\nportant reaction. A short tech\nnical correction seems probable.\u2014\nOTIS CO.\nAlthough we believe the trend\nmay continue upward, reactions\nshould be seen this afternoon or\nWednesday. Purchases on de\nclines may be made in the bet-\nIter stocks.\u2014John MUIR CO. j'\nThink that the low average\nprices for the year hava been\nseen and that the market is g\npurchase on all fair reactions.\u2014\nTOBEY KIRK.\nThe manner in which the mar\nket moved ahead yesterday indi\ncates there is little stock for sale.\nSuch condition could easily result\nin a gradually rising market.-*\nMELADY CO.\nThe market passed through the\nresistance points so successfully\nthat it is impossible to set* the\nlimits on the current rally.\u2014\nHORNBLOWER WEEKS.\nI Cosy homes suitable to th*\nneeds of every prospective home.euycr,\nare listed for yoor convenience' of so\nlection in today\u2019s Classified Ads.\n25","height":"30453","width":"24271"}}
